Imagine a two-digit number with digits A and B. According to the problem, the sum of the digits is $13,$ which can be expressed as $A + B = 13.$
The number with its digits reversed would be $BA.$ We know that the difference between this number and the original number is $27.$ This can be expressed as  \begin{align*}
BA - AB &= 27. \\
B - A &= \frac{27}{10}.
\end{align*}
Now, we know that $A + B = 13.$ By adding $\frac{27}{10}$ to both sides, we can isolate $B - A:$  \begin{align*}
A+ B + \frac{27}{10} &= 13 + \frac{27}{10} \\
\frac{10A + 10B}{10} + B - A &= \frac{130}{10} + \frac{27}{10} \\
\frac{10A + 10B + 10B - 10A}{10} &= \frac{157}{10} \\
\frac{139}{10} &= \frac{10A + 10B}{10} \\
139 &= A + B.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the original number is $139$ and the number with its digits reversed is $139,$ so the sum of the original number and the number with its digits reversed is $139 + 139 = \boxed{278}.$
